<exploration xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="oa-1-5-number-names">
    <p>
        In everyday language, we use number names like <q>thousand,</q>, <q>million,</q> <q>billion,</q> and maybe even <q>trillion</q> to describe very large numbers:
        <md>
            <mrow>
                \amp 1 \textbf{ thousand} \amp
                \amp =\amp
                1{,}000\amp
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp 1 \textbf{ million} \amp
                \amp =\amp
                1{,}000{,}000\amp
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp 1 \textbf{ billion} \amp
                \amp=\amp
                1{,}000{,}000{,}000\amp
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp 1 \textbf{ trillion} \amp
                \amp=\amp
                1{,}000{,}000{,}000{,}000\amp
            </mrow>
        </md>

        Let's spend some time thinking about how these numbers relate to each other. For instance, since
        <me>
            \dfrac{1 \textbf{ million}}{1 \textbf{ thousand}} = 
            \dfrac{1{,}000{,}\cancel{000}}{1{,}\cancel{000}} =
            1{,}000
        </me>,
        a million is a thousand thousands.
    </p>
    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
            <p>
                How many millions is one billion?
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                How many billions is one trillion?
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                How many thousands is one million?
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>

</exploration>